<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-01-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-01-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="37" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d37">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5801</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chinese Ministry of Foreign
                                    Affairs</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Chinese
                                Legation</gloss></hi><note n="57" xml:id="d37fn57">Copy of telegram
                                transmitted to the Department by the Chinese Legation on January
                                9.</note></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-01-09">January 9, 1933</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Marshal Chang Hsiao-Liang, in an interview given to Chinese and foreign
                            correspondents, declared: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Since international peace efforts appear to have ceased to be
                                    effective, I see no way to maintain peace and protect China
                                    except through sacrificing our lives and blood.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>